  "prompt": "Why doesn't India ban the import of Chinese goods as answer to its stance on NSG?",
  "response": "The reasons why India has not banned Chinese goods despite tensions include:\n\n1. Economic interdependence\n- China is India's largest trading partner\n- Significant trade volume ($135.98 billion in 2022)\n- Sudden ban could harm Indian industries and consumers\n\n2. Supply chain complexities\n- Many Indian industries depend on Chinese raw materials and components\n- Immediate replacement would be challenging and expensive\n\n3. Economic implications\n- Potential job losses in import-dependent sectors\n- Higher consumer prices\n- Disruption of manufacturing ecosystems\n\n4. Strategic considerations\n- Maintaining some economic engagement despite political tensions\n- Avoiding complete economic decoupling\n\n5. World Trade Organization (WTO) regulations\n- Unilateral bans could violate international trade rules\n- Potential legal challenges and retaliatory measures\n\n6. Gradual trade diversification strategy\n- India is slowly reducing dependence through \"Atmanirbhar Bharat\" (self-reliant India) policy\n- Promoting domestic manufacturing\n- Seeking alternative import sources\n\n7. Diplomatic balance\n- Avoiding escalation of tensions\n- Keeping communication channels open\n\nWhile India has implemented some restrictive measures and increased scrutiny on Chinese imports, a complete ban remains economically unfeasible.",
